> I've built the two core safety components we discussed:
> 
> **1. BudgetController** (`code/budget_controller.py`)
> 
> Prevents runaway API costs:
> - Hard cap on calls per run (default: 100 calls)
> - Hard cap on total spend (default: $10 USD)
> - Result caching (never evaluate same input twice)
> - Cost estimation and logging per model
> - Emergency shutoff when limits reached
> 
> Usage:
> ```python
> budget = BudgetController(max_calls=100, max_cost_usd=5.0)
> 
> # Before API call
> budget.check_budget("gemini-pro", estimated_cost=0.02)
> 
> # Check cache
> cache_key = budget.get_cache_key(context, task)
> if cached := budget.check_cache(cache_key):
>     return cached
> 
> # Make call
> result = evaluator.judge(a, b)
> 
> # Record usage
> budget.record_call("gemini-pro", cost=0.018)
> budget.cache_result(cache_key, result)
> ```
> 
> **2. CalibrationMonitor** (`code/calibration_monitor.py`)
> 
> Detects evaluator gaming through three mechanisms:
> 
> a) **Canary tests**: Known-bad contexts that should score poorly
>    - If canaries start scoring well → evaluators fooled
>    - Includes: empty docstrings, gibberish, wrong language
> 
> b) **Holdout validation**: Contexts hidden from search
>    - If archive >> holdout → overfitting to evaluators
>    - Classic ML defense adapted to evolutionary search
> 
> c) **Temporal drift**: Re-evaluation of old contexts
>    - If old contexts degrade on re-eval → calibration shifted
>    - Measures fitness landscape drift
> 
> Usage:
> ```python
> monitor = CalibrationMonitor(
>     evaluator_ensemble=judge_pool,
>     canaries=create_standard_canaries(),
>     holdout_set=[...]
> )
> 
> # During QD search (every N iterations)
> if iteration % 50 == 0:
>     report = monitor.check_calibration(archive, iteration)
>     if not report.is_healthy():
>         print("⚠️  EVALUATOR GAMING DETECTED!")
>         for warning in report.warnings:
>             print(f"  - {warning.message}")
> ```
